use, Bridport, Dorset, England":"Bridport, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Carew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, James Patrick, Kieran.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire): habitational name from any of various minor places in Wales, in particular one near Pembroke with a major castle, named from Welsh <i>caer</i> ‘fort’ + <i>rhiw</i> ‘hill, slope’. The surname was taken to Ireland soon after the Norman invasion of England and was Gaelicized as <b>de Carrún</b>. In the 16th century a family called <i>Carew</i> from Devon played an important part in establishing the Tudor administration in Ireland.","Cornish (Somerset and Devon): from the cognate Cornish word <i>kerrow</i> (plural of <i>ker</i> ‘fort’), which occurs seven times as a placename in Cornwall."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Carew was born in 1346, in Buckinghamshire, England, his father, Si